SI618 Lab 9¶

In this lab, we will be working with three different datasets

  1. The UCI data set about wine quality from lab 8. The dataset comes from https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/red-wine-quality-cortez-et-al-2009
  2. Selected gender inequality related data from global development database downloaded from the World Bank data bank (https://databank.worldbank.org/reports.aspx?source=world-development-indicators#). Read the metadata file for more information about the two variables being used.
  3. A monthly time series dataset of the number of domestic airline passengers (in 000s) in the United States collected from https://www.transtats.bts.gov/TRAFFIC/

  • Use a JointGrid approach look at the relationship between sulphates and alcohol.
  • Look at the same relationship separately for good and bad wines with separate JointGrids
  • What do you observe?

Hint: When appropriate, create additional figures that allow you to exclude the effect of outliers

Question 2: (15 points) Use OLS to perform either a regression or an ANOVA for the relationship between sulphates with (i) categorical variable of wine quality and (ii) original quality. Interpret your results.¶

In [7]:
import statsmodels.api as sm
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
In [8]:
model = smf.ols('sulphates ~ C(isgood)', data=wine).fit()
model.summary()

aov_table = sm.stats.anova_lm(model, typ=2)
print(aov_table)

              sum_sq      df         F        PR(>F)

From this table we can see that the p-value is very small, less than 0.05. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis that good and bad wines have the same mean sulphates values, which means that sulphates does not have a strong relationship with whether the wine is good or bad.

As a whole, the proportion of women in the legislature has increased to a greater or lesser extent in all the ten countries.
The difference is that in some countries there is only a very slight variation in the proportion of women, such as Nigeria.
In some countries, there is a clear upward trend in the proportion of women, but the change is relatively small, such as China, Brazil and India.
In some countries, the proportion of women is not only increasing, but also changing very much, such as Mexico and the United States.
There are countries where there are ups and downs in the proportion of women, but overall it is still increasing, such as Bangladesh, Indonesia, and Pakistan.

Question 7: (15 points) Remove the monthly seasonal effect from the passenger time series and plot the adjusted passenger (mean + residual) time series. What do you observe?¶

In [29]:
model = smf.ols('Passengers ~ C(month)', data=airline).fit()
airline['Passengers_ds'] = model.resid
In [30]:
avg = stat_summary(aes(group = 1), fun_y = np.mean, geom = "line", colour = "red", size = 2, na_rm = True) 

line = geom_smooth(aes(group = 1),method='lm')
ggplot(airline, aes('Period', 'Passengers_ds')) + avg + line + \
  ggtitle("Deseasonified passengers by month with seasonal trendline") + \
  geom_line() + geom_point() + scale_x_datetime(breaks=date_breaks('2 years'), labels=date_format('%Y-%m')) + theme(figure_size=(10, 6))
Out[30]:
<ggplot: (8766566005035)>

We can see more clearly that the number of passengers tends to increase with the month. What is more noteworthy is that there was a sharp drop starting from about 2008-03.
